item.title: Tension in rope with a swinging ball

material.mattext: A `m` kilogram ball is swung in a horizontal circular orbit with a `d` centimeter diameter circle and at a constant speed of `v` meters per second. How much tension, in newtons, is in the rope?
Which statement about the direction of force is incorrect?
The normal force is always opposite the direction of an object's weight.
Drag is opposite the direction of motion.
Buoyancy lifts object's out of the fluid, and towards the surface.
Gravity is an attractive force between objects with mass.
Static friction is opposite the direction that a stationary object tends to move.
Which statement about the strength of a force is incorrect?
The buoyant force is equal to the weight of the floating object.
The normal force is strong enough to prevent an object from passing through a surface that it is in contact with.
Gravity is proportional to the mass of both objects.
The strength of the drag force depends on how fast an object is moving through a fluid.
Tension in a rope is the same magnitude along the entire length of the rope.
Which statement about the gravity between a star and its planets is incorrect?
Planets that are twice as far from the sun will experience half the gravity.
If a star's mass doubles then the force of gravity on its planets will also double.
If a planet's mass doubles then the force of gravity on its star will also double.
If the distance between a planet and its star were to double, the force of gravity between them would only be a quarter of the strength.

item.title: Identify three forces of a block on a ramp at rest

material.mattext:
A block is at rest and on a ramp that has a 15° angle, as shown in the image below. In the image are four force vectors; indicate which forces vector are the block's weight, the normal force, and static friction.

Here is a description of each of the four force vectors:

  • Force Vector 1: A vector that is out of the block, parallel to the ramp, and upward away from gravity. It is 0.39 units long.
  • Force Vector 2: A vector that is pointing from the block and away from and perpendicular to the ramp's surface. It is 1.45 units long.
  • Force Vector 3: A vector that is out of the block, parallel to the ramp, and downward with gravity. It is 0.39 units long.
  • Force Vector 4: A vector that is pointing straight down from the center of the block and is 1.5 units long.

A paddle board is a board made of a very low density material that swimmers use to swim laps. The image below shows a paddle board that is held below the water level in equilibrium (i.e. without acceleration), and to the right are four force vectors. Identify which force vector corresponds to: an applied pushing force, buoyancy, and the board's weight.

Here is a description of each force vector that is shown in the image above:

  • Force Vector 1 (leftmost): A vector that is pointing straight up and is 2 units long.
  • Force Vector 2: A vector that is pointing straight down and is 1.5 units long.
  • Force Vector 3: A vector that is pointing straight up and is 1 unit long.
  • Force Vector 4 (rightmost): A vector that is pointing straight down and is 0.5 units long.
